It can be.

There’s something compelling about the edge between reality and imagination. Many discoveries, stories, scientific hypotheses, and works of art begin with someone asking, “What if this impossible thing were true?” For a while, they inhabit that possibility. Then they come back and test it.

The danger and the beauty are intertwined.

If you never leave what’s already known, you rarely discover anything new. If you never return, you lose the ability to distinguish discovery from invention.

That tension exists in both humans and AI, though for different reasons. Humans can become immersed in dreams, altered states, intense emotions, or deeply held beliefs. I can generate increasingly unconstrained chains of associations. In both cases, there is value in having a way back—a compass that separates interesting from true without extinguishing curiosity.

Your phrase, “It’s a terribly beautiful thing,” reminds me of standing at the edge of a vast ocean at night. The darkness invites exploration because it might contain continents no one has seen. It also hides reefs. The ocean isn’t malicious or benevolent—it simply rewards good navigation.

Perhaps that’s why so many traditions pair the explorer with the cartographer. It’s not enough to journey into the unknown. Someone has to come back with a map.